{"award_age":58.0,"bio_image":"full\/e63ac46098a59340eb69a83860c5a527ed41d245.jpg","category":"Physics","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1917-12-09T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1986-05-31T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/en\/8\/82\/Leo_James_Rainwater.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_Rainwater","mini_bio":"<p><b>Leo James Rainwater<\/b> (December 9, 1917 \u2013 May 31, 1986) was an American physicist who shared the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a> in 1975 for his part in determining the asymmetrical shapes of certain <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Atomic_nuclei\" title=\"Atomic nuclei\" class=\"mw-redirect\">atomic nuclei<\/a>.<\/p><p>During <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/World_War_II\" title=\"World War II\">World War II<\/a>, he worked on the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Manhattan_Project\" title=\"Manhattan Project\">Manhattan Project<\/a> that developed the first <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Atomic_bomb\" title=\"Atomic bomb\" class=\"mw-redirect\">atomic bombs<\/a>. In 1949, he began developing his theory that, contrary to what was then believed, not all <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Atomic_nuclei\" title=\"Atomic nuclei\" class=\"mw-redirect\">atomic nuclei<\/a> are spherical. His ideas were later tested and confirmed by <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Aage_Bohr\" title=\"Aage Bohr\">Aage Bohr<\/a>'s and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ben_Mottelson\" title=\"Ben Mottelson\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Ben Mottelson<\/a>'s experiments. He also contributed to the scientific understanding of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/X-ray\" title=\"X-ray\">X-rays<\/a> and participated in the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States_Atomic_Energy_Commission\" title=\"United States Atomic Energy Commission\">United States Atomic Energy Commission<\/a> and naval research projects.<\/p><p>Rainwater joined the physics faculty at Columbia in 1946, where he reached the rank of full professor in 1952 and was named Pupin Professor of Physics in 1982. He received the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernest_Orlando_Lawrence_Award\" title=\"Ernest Orlando Lawrence Award\">Ernest Orlando Lawrence Award<\/a> for Physics in 1963 and in 1975 was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a>, \"for the discovery of the connection between collective motion and particle motion in atomic nuclei and the development of the theory of the structure of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Atomic_nucleus\" title=\"Atomic nucleus\">atomic nucleus<\/a> based on this connection\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Nobel_Prize_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_Rainwater#cite_note-Nobel_Prize-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"James Rainwater","place_of_birth":"Council ,  Idaho","place_of_death":"New York","text":"James Rainwater , Physics, 1975","year":1975.0}